<div id="reset"><span style="left:6px;top:50px;position:relative;font-family:Outfit,sans-serif">Reset?</span></div><div class="parent"><div class="gamecontainer hoverer"><div id="game"></div><p>Glasses of Water:</p></div><div id="levelCounter">Level: 1</div><div id="scoreCounter">Score: 0</div><div class="title-screen" id="titleScreen" style="opacity:1;font-family:Outfit,sans-serif"><div class="title">UNTITLED WATER DRINKING GAME II</div><span class="fades" style="margin:5px auto;font-size:.7em">ENTER TO START</span><br><div class="instructions" style="margin-block:5px">USE ARROW KEYS OR D-PAD<br><span class="rgb" style="font-weight:900">YOU</span>: COLLECT AT LEAST 3<span style="color:#00f;font-weight:900">WATERS</span><br>AVOID<span style="color:#000;font-weight:900">POLLUTION</span><br><span style="color:#cfc;font-weight:900">TRACTOR BEAM</span>(5s),<span style="color:#ffb3ff;font-weight:900">DOUBLE JUMP</span>(5s)<br>FIND THE<span style="color:#ff0;font-weight:900">YELLOW</span>DOOR.</div></div><div class="controls"><div class="d-pad"><div class="button" data-action="enter">ENT</div><div class="button" data-action="up">↑</div><div class="button" data-action="sound">VOL</div><div class="button" data-action="left">←</div><div class="button" data-action="down">↓</div><div class="button" data-action="right">→</div></div></div><div class="bar-container"><div class="loading-bar"></div><div class="loading-bar2"></div></div><div id="prestigeCounter">Prestige Level: 0</div><div id="drinkSpeedCounter">Drink Speed: 0ms</div><div id="tokenCounter">Drink Tokens: 1</div><div id="kismetCounter">Kismet Factor: 1</div><br><div id="row1" class="row"><div id="plustwomulti" class="column disable"></div><div id="autodrink" class="column disable"></div></div><br><div id="row2" class="row"><div id="prestige" class="column disable"></div><div id="stop" class="column disable"></div></div><br><div id="row3" class="row"><div class="boxTitle" style="clear:both"><p>change comes from within</p><div class="rulebox" style="text-align:left"><p>1.<span class="rules1 disable">add 2 × multiplier² / tap</span></p><p>2.<span class="rules2 disable">speed up & autodrink</span></p><p>3.<span class="rules3 disable">return (prestige)</span></p><p>4.<span class="rules4 disable">stop</span></p></div></div></div><div class="messageWarn">NOTES</div><br><div class="msDiv1">Eight glasses in, and you begin to feel the opposite of how you thought you'd feel. You've always been dehydrated, from cigarettes and shitty weed to sodas and other forms of neglect. The inside of your mouth tastes like nothing, a dry, pasty film of absence, at least at first. Soon, the water quickly overpowers it with a metallic and unsavory flavor. It lays heavy in your stomach. You resist the urge to vomit. Instead, you spend an unknown amount of time gripping your abdomen and hoping the pain comes to an end. Physical pain, but emotional pain too. Years and years of pollutants, built up within a home, extracted via tap, and filtered through Alex Thorley.<br><br>You'd rid the world of pain, one household at a time, if you could, and maybe then, by changing everything else, you could change, too. You could be like everyone else. You could be "normal". You could have thoughts and feelings and sensations that made sense to anyone else outside of your head.<br><br>The dark toxins embedding themselves inside you feel odd, as if you ate a handful of buckshot. They burrow their way down into the flesh of your stomach and hold tight with tiny, sharp barbs. You know they won't be leaving any time soon, but it hardly matters when you don't exist. You instead disconnect from corporeal form, as if you were wearing clothes gifted to you by someone who knew you'd hate it.<br><br>I just hope this is all worth it, Alex. Has it been? Worth it, I mean. Do you feel more connected with yourself? Or was all this just another distraction from your own poisoned well, which left you tied up in threads you wove to balance precariously what everyone else does so effortlessly?<br><br>Do you feel any different? Do you<em>feel</em>at all?<br><br>8 down, 708 to go.<br><br></div><div class="msDiv2">Three days have passed. Or, rather, three days' worth of waters have been consumed. Why you decided to track time based on water consumption is not clear, but the fact that you misplaced your watch last week doesn't help the uncertainty. You can't even trust your phone anymore, considering how often you lose service. It definitely felt like three days, but you weren't paying attention that closely. The sun sets and rises, but the actual date doesn't tend to match its cycles. It's by design, of course.<br><br>The cramps have worsened, but also eased. They're constant, but diminished, reducing to a dull ache with occasional spikes of distress that make your teeth hurt. You wish you could drink something else, but that's not how this works. You are to subsist only on tap water.<em>It won't be that bad once you're used to it,</em>you tell yourself.<br><br>You're pretty sure that's a lie.<br><br>Time begins to slip by.<br><br><div class="buttonholder"><button id="unlock-1" class="mod">1</button></div><br></div><div class="msDiv3"><br>You might as well have been sucking on a fork for a week. You wished you brought gum, but then you remembered your favorite brand is known to cause cancer in the State of California, and that's where you are currently. You think. You don't really look at where you're going, or remember how you get there. You have directions and a sense of following them. Before you know it, you're in another stranger's kitchen, drinking their water for them.<br><br>This house's tap water is lukewarm and doesn't want to be any colder. Their ice trays are empty. The house feels devoid of emotion, but maybe you're just projecting.<br><br>If that was the case, who removed the photos from the walls, and why?<br><br>Maybe contaminated water isn't the only toxic thing to come out of this situation.<br><br></div><div class="msDiv4"><br>You've begun to notice subtle notes in different glasses of wellwater. City water almost always tastes the same, but wellwater is like a fine wine, and you a somolier. You swirl the glass in hand, sip and swish. You force yourself to swallow.<br><br>Delicious.<br><br></div><div class="msDiv5"><br>The human body can typically survive up to three days without water. Without food, it's closer to a month. You've done the math. Eight glasses a day would mean one hundred and twenty-five days of dieting only on polluted water, but you're pretty sure you'll be fine. You're not a Typical Human, after all.<br><br>Still, the fine tremor developing in your hands is a tad worrying. How long will this last once you finish what you have to do? If things like lead and Pentadecafluorooctanoic acid stayed in you forever, could there really be a "safe level" one can ingest?<br><br>You don't think so. All the more reason to keep drinking. It's damage other people won't be doing to themselves, and your urine is as sterile as the offspring of people who drink contaminated water. Hypothetically speaking, of course. Those people wouldn't exist once you finished your task at hand.<br><br>Just gotta stop thinking about it. Go on autopilot. You do autopilot so well as it is. Just let your eyes glaze over as the clock turns sideways.<br><br><div class="buttonholder"><button id="unlock-2" class="mod">2</button></div><br></div><div class="msDiv6"><br>Is it cheating to get essential minerals and vitamins from glacial basin tapwater? It feels like cheating, but goddamn is this stuff good compared to oil field swill or the treated runoff of the Gowanus. You shiver at the thought of it.<br><br>The pain has nearly stopped, by the way. If everything hurts, it's like nothing hurts.<br><br>You ignore the implications of that and continue onward. You've got to be getting close now, right?<br><br>Right?<br></div><div class="msDiv7"><br>Your mood fluctuates from home to home, from glass to glass. Your first drink in each new location used to be interesting and exciting, in a fucked up, I'm-definitely-making-progress sort of way. Now, the nausea is a constant but distant feeling. You don't care about it, because it can't touch the<em>real</em>you. The one that exists without the form, the Self. You are an enlightened monk, free from the confines of physical limitation.<br><br>You could really go for a fucking cigarette right now.</div><div class="msDiv8"><br>You dropped a glass at a stranger's McMansion today. It shattered so loudly it jolted you awake. Was it the fact that you were asleep what caused you to drop it, or was it the fact that you can't keep your hands still enough to avoid spilling water on yourself when you go to take a sip of that lightly opaque, life-giving liquid you so swore to conquer?<br><br>Is this what you wanted? Do you feel closer to yourself?<br><br>Would you change your decision, or do it over again?<br><br></div><div class="msDiv9"><br>Have you been drinking water for your entire life? It feels like someone tricked you into doing something wrong since you were very little. Why would anyone put this stuff into their body? The particles of adulterant weigh heavy on you. The weight of every life hanging in the balance weighs heavy on you. The world feels heavy. Your limbs feel heavy. But you've done it, you think.<br><br>You could really go for a fucking nap right now, but there are still other wells to purify. There is more than one player in this game of negligence and birth defects. The rest await your helping hand, sickly and fragile it may be. Food isn't necessary. Sleep, a far-off dream.<br><br><em>You'll sleep when you're dead,</em>you tell yourself. You're pretty sure you don't mean that literally.<br><div class="buttonholder"><button id="unlock-3" class="mod">3</button></div><br></div><br><div class="msDivFin"><br>You'll keep drinking till the bitter end. Right?<br><br>It's an endless task, but someone has to do it. Right?<br><br>You can't stop now. You don't want to stop now. Not when you're so close, you think.<br><br>Do you want to stop? Can you stop?<br><br>Your phone rings.<br><br>A hand brings it up an ear. Your ear. One of them. You're pretty sure.<br><br>"Alex?"<br><br>You haven't spoken in what must be months. When you use your voice, it's almost as if you haven't been drinking water this entire time.<br><br>"Who is this?"<br><br>The answer takes a little longer than you'd prefer to reveal itself.<br><br>"We're here on behalf of Alex Thorley. They want you to return. It's not working out."<br><br>"What do you mean, 'not working out'?"<br><br>"Have you heard of DuPont de Nemours?"<br><br>"I haven't taken French since high school."<br><br>Another pause. This time, indefinite. Until you speak again, anyway.<br><br>"Did I do it? Did I change the world?"<br><br>"You could say that, but I don't think you'd want to."<br><br>You don't remember the rest of that conversation.<br><br><div class="buttonholder"><button id="unlock-4" class="mod">4</button></div><br></div><div class="hiddens"><br>Alex Thorley was a lot of things. Thorley was an employee of the Foundation, and handled job duties of various types, presumably. They were aloof at times, troubled at others, and could detect a good bagel with any four of their five senses restricted.<br><br>Mostly, though, Alex Thorley was alone. Despite being a good friend, they were nearly always alone. You might not see it when they pass by, because Alex went to exceptional lengths to pretend everything was okay.<br><br>Unfortunately, such efforts are largely unsustainable. Simple tasks grew to be insurmountable heaps of effort. Energy doled out in<em>spoons</em>and<em>good days</em>, which dwindled with time.<br><br>Many thousands of random moments became a technicolor, riling gyre within their mind. Despite those many shades living within that existential soup, when zoomed out it grew uniform. Like a shade of gray-white that no pleasant attributions could be assigned to.<br><br>This is why Alex tried to do what they did. It's why they failed, and succeeded.<br><br>It's why Thorley found a black business card under the door to their office one morning, before deciding whether or not to leave and begin drinking water, again. Not doing so would mean another Thorley, somewhere, would cease existing. An entire timeline would cease existing.<br><br>The researcher thought for a long while about this, or perhaps for not long at all. A black rotary phone began to ring within the office, one that had not been there before. Thorley looked to their wrist and realized they were not wearing a watch.<br><br><em>Fuck it.</em>They picked up the receiver. A voice on the other line spoke in harsh tones and contextless noises. After a moment, the line went dead.<br>Thorley returned the phone to its cradle and felt a bit funny. Something was different. Who knows what that could mean?<br><br>They turned the card over in their hands, looking down at the gold-embossed text reading<a href="/deleted">"U5-Ⰲ"</a>, and nothing more. They had no idea what it meant, but it felt important.<br><br>Thorley stayed inside that day, and cleaned their office for the first time in forever.<br><br></div><div class="messageWarn">ACHIEVEMENTS</div><br><div class="achievement-container" style="margin-bottom:20px"><div class="image-slot disable"><img src="https://scpdsandbox.wdfiles.com/local--files/billith9/agua.png" title="You got the achievement 'Hydrate'!"></div><div class="image-slot disable"><img src="https://scpdsandbox.wdfiles.com/local--files/billith9/barry.png" title="You got the achievement 'Barry the Bagel'!"></div><div class="image-slot disable"><img src="https://scpdsandbox.wdfiles.com/local--files/billith9/rarebagel.png" title="You got the achievement 'Rare Bagel'!"></div><div class="image-slot disable"><img src="https://scpdsandbox.wdfiles.com/local--files/billith9/duponce.png" title="You got the achievement 'DuPonce'!"></div><div class="image-slot disable"><img src="https://scpdsandbox.wdfiles.com/local--files/billith9/earthly.png" title="You got the achievement 'Earthly'!"></div><div class="image-slot disable"><img src="https://scpdsandbox.wdfiles.com/local--files/billith9/wavey.png" title="You got the achievement 'Waves'!"></div><div class="image-slot disable"><img src="https://scpdsandbox.wdfiles.com/local--files/billith9/notfound.png" title="You got the achievement 'Dept. Not Found'!"></div><div class="image-slot disable"><img src="https://scpdsandbox.wdfiles.com/local--files/billith9/plaid.png" title="You got the achievement 'Odd Water'!"></div></div><audio id="jumpSound" src="http://scpdsandbox.wikidot.com/local--files/billith9/jump.ogg"></audio><audio id="collectSound" src="http://scpdsandbox.wikidot.com/local--files/billith9/water.ogg"></audio><audio id="powerUpSound" src="http://scpdsandbox.wikidot.com/local--files/billith9/powerup.ogg"></audio><audio id="doorSound" src="http://scpdsandbox.wikidot.com/local--files/billith9/levelup.ogg"></audio><audio id="gameOverSound" src="http://scpdsandbox.wikidot.com/local--files/billith9/gameover.ogg"></audio><audio id="backgroundMusic" src="http://scpdsandbox.wikidot.com/local--files/billith9/thirst.ogg"></audio><br><br>
